seiu negotiations 2009 page 1 issue 5 august 7 2009 from the stanford bargaining team welcome to the fifth edition of the stanford seiu bargaining update in connection with stanford university's contract negotiations with the service employees international union local 2007 seiu on july 7 2009 stanford and seiu began negotiations for a new collective bargaining agreement for approximately 1200 employees in schools and departments across the university including the slac national laboratory this weekly update which will be available during these negotiations will provide information about ideas and interests discussed options tentatively agreed to or other outcomes please disseminate the update as needed stanford and the seiu concludes 5th week of bargaining stanford and seiu concluded the 5th week of negotiations with tentative agreements in the following areas health and safety committees establishing a new steering committee charged with studying best practices across the campus recommending goal oriented plans with benchmarks focused on injury prevention and making recommendations for bargaining unit wide training alternative work schedules which establishes the rules by which alternative work schedules are governed when proposed by stanford management the parties also held meaningful discussions with respect to reforming the step progression structure with an eye towards slowing the pace of advancement by lengthening the current progression schedule the union also shared its interest in creating more robust apprenticeship opportunities specifically in the skilled trades the small joint working group addressing issues related to the grounds and paint units of land buildings and real estate continued their work by modeling options designed to achieve cost savings while attempting to preserve jobs the union reaffirmed its commitment to finding solutions which help stanford to operate a more competitive grounds unit while working to stem any job loss the parties resume negotiations on tuesday august 11 2009 the agenda will include reviewing supposals a hypothetical proposal related to reforming the step progression structure and framework for improving apprenticeship opportunities page 2 issue 5 august 7 2009 the stanford bargaining team the stanford bargaining team includes david a jones director employee & management services human resources ann allison marsh senior manager employee & labor relations human resources cori bossenberry director of human resources school of medicine robert carpenter director of operations buildings and grounds maintenance land buildings and real estate megan davis associate vice president finance land buildings and real estate eric montell executive director stanford dining residential and dining enterprises and larry young director of human resources slac national laboratory
